# Experimental Platform Support

This folder contains extended platform support that goes beyond the
hardware-confirmed fixes in the main `me_cleaner.py`. The changes here
are based on community reverse engineering, Intel PCH datasheet analysis,
and consensus — not direct hardware flashing by this repo's maintainer
(except where noted).

**Use at your own risk. Always make a full backup of your firmware before
flashing. An incorrect HAP patch that silently writes to the wrong location
will appear to succeed but ME will not be disabled.**

---

## me_cleaner_experimental.py

A drop-in replacement for `me_cleaner.py` that adds support for newer
Intel platforms on top of the stable hardware-confirmed fork.

### What's in the stable fork (unchanged here)

| ME Version | Platform | HAP Location | Status |
|---|---|---|---|
| ME 12 LP | Cannon Lake / Whiskey Lake (8th/9th gen U) | `fpsba+0x70` PCHSTRP28 bit 16 | ✅ Hardware confirmed |
| ME 12 H | Cannon Lake H / Z390 desktop | `fpsba+0x80` PCHSTRP32 bit 16 | ✅ Hardware confirmed via PR#282 |
| ME 13 | Ice Lake (10th gen LP) | `fpsba+0x70` PCHSTRP28 bit 16 | ✅ Datasheet confirmed (Doc 615170) |
| ME 14 | Comet Lake LP (10th gen) | `fpsba+0x70` PCHSTRP28 bit 16 | ✅ Hardware confirmed (X13 Gen1) |

### What's new in experimental

| ME Version | Platform | HAP Location | Status |
|---|---|---|---|
| ME 15 | Tiger Lake (11th gen) | `fpsba+0x7C` PCHSTRP31 bit 16 | ⚠️ Community confirmed, not hw tested here |
| ME 16 | Alder Lake (12th gen) | `fpsba+0x7C` PCHSTRP31 bit 16 = byte `0x017E` | ✅ Datasheet confirmed (Doc 648364) |
| ME 16.1 | Raptor Lake (13th gen) | `fpsba+0x7C` PCHSTRP31 bit 16 = byte `0x017E` | ✅ Datasheet confirmed (Doc 743835) |
| ME 18 | Meteor Lake (14th gen) | **UNKNOWN** — current write is a placeholder | ❌ Unconfirmed — do not rely on |

---

## ADL/RPL HAP Location — Correction vs Other Forks

The HAP bit on Alder Lake and Raptor Lake **did not move out of the PCH
Straps**. It is still PCHSTRP31 bit 16 — the same register as Tiger Lake.

Writing to byte `0x017E` and writing to `fpsba+0x7C` bit 16 are
**identical operations**:

```
fpsba         = 0x100        (confirmed, Intel 600/700-series PCH datasheets)
PCHSTRP31     = fpsba + 0x7C = 0x17C   (the 32-bit strap dword)
byte 0x017E   = 0x17C + 2    = byte 2 of that dword = bits 16–23
bit 16        = bit 0 of byte 0x017E
```

Some community forks (including XutaxKamay PR #384) originally guessed
`fpsba+0xDC` (PCHSTRP55). That is wrong — confirmed by direct analysis
of Intel 600-series PCH Datasheet Vol1 (Doc 648364) and 700-series
(Doc 743835).

---

## MTL Warning

Meteor Lake (ME 18) has a completely different descriptor layout. There
are **no PCH Straps at `0x100`** on MTL. The HAP bit likely lives in
IOE Soft Straps at `0xCAC`, but this has not been empirically confirmed.

The current code writes to `0x017E` when ME 18 is detected and prints
a runtime warning. This write is almost certainly wrong on MTL and may
have no effect. A new gen 8 path will be added once the HAP offset is
confirmed from a real MTL firmware dump.

**Do not flash an MTL image based on this tool without first confirming
the HAP offset.**

---

## Internal Generation Map

The script maps ME version numbers to internal "generation" codes:

| ME Version | Platform | Internal gen | HAP write |
|---|---|---|---|
| 12 | Cannon/Whiskey Lake | gen 4 | `fpsba+0x70` or `+0x80` (LP/H heuristic) |
| 13 | Ice Lake | gen 4 | `fpsba+0x70` PCHSTRP28 |
| 14 | Comet Lake LP | gen 5 | `fpsba+0x70` PCHSTRP28 (hardcoded, hw confirmed) |
| 15 | Tiger Lake | gen 6 | `fpsba+0x7C` PCHSTRP31 |
| 16 / 16.1 | Alder / Raptor Lake | gen 7 | byte write to `0x017E` = PCHSTRP31 bit 16 |
| 18 | Meteor Lake | gen 7 ⚠️ | byte write to `0x017E` — **PLACEHOLDER, likely wrong** |

---

## Usage

Identical to the original me_cleaner:

```bash
# Set HAP bit only (recommended for all IFWI firmware — ME 12+)
python3 me_cleaner_experimental.py -s firmware.bin -O firmware_hap.bin

# Check status only — does not modify anything
python3 me_cleaner_experimental.py -c firmware.bin

# Set HAP and strip modules (older pre-IFWI platforms only)
python3 me_cleaner_experimental.py -S firmware.bin -O firmware_hap.bin
```

> On gen 4+ (ME 12 and newer) the tool automatically detects IFWI firmware
> and skips module stripping with a warning, only setting the HAP bit.
> This is the correct and safe behaviour for all modern platforms.

---

## Verifying Before You Flash

After patching, always check with MEAnalyzer before flashing:

```bash
python3 MEAnalyzer.py firmware_hap.bin
```

Look for:
```
HAP/AltMeDisable: Yes
```

If it says `No` — the patch did not apply correctly. Do not flash.

---

## After Flashing — Confirming ME Is Disabled

```bash
# Should return nothing
lspci | grep -i mei

# Should report no device
sudo ./intelmetool -m
```

On a correctly patched machine:
- `lspci` returns nothing for MEI
- BIOS ME version field is blank
- intelmetool cannot find a device

See [ME_Disable_Comparison.md](../ME_Disable_Comparison.md) for a full
breakdown of what to expect per platform.

---

## Please Report Your Results

If you test on any experimental platform, open an issue and include:

- Machine model
- ME version (from MEAnalyzer on stock firmware)
- Platform (TGL / ADL / RPL / MTL)
- Whether MEAnalyzer shows `HAP/AltMeDisable: Yes` after patching
- Whether ME was absent after flashing (`lspci`, BIOS ME field)

Enough confirmed reports will promote a platform to the stable `me_cleaner.py`.

